<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-29T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-29T06:00:00-05:00" n="406" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d406">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 659.119/354</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Denmark</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GSU1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grant-Smith</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                        <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Copenhagen</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-29T12:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">June 29, 1918, noon.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.57 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2452. Delegates of Central Powers will begin negotiations with Danish
                                associations July 8, in Copenhagen, for new four months’ arrangement
                                for the exchange of products. Iron and steel manufactures important
                                articles for which Germany will receive compensation. Is War Trade
                                Board prepared to license immediately 1,500 <pb facs="0497" n="1331" xml:id="pg_1331"/> to 2,000 tons of wrought iron tubing for
                                prompt shipment to weaken enemy’s position in negotiations?
                                Indication on our part to raise embargo on iron and steel products
                                will not alone serve to reduce quantities which Germany will receive
                                in compensation but will tend to reduce prices demanded. Urgent.
                                Copy to London.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GSU1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grant-Smith</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>